post_text:
UPDATE: Section IX Athletic Council approves plan for 2020-21 sports

Today the Section IX Athletic Council approved an opening date for athletics for all Section IX schools, which includes Monroe-Woodbury. The following decisions were made:

The Fall Season has been moved to the spring and will begin in March 2021. The official start date is still to be determined.
The Winter Season will begin November 30, 2020.
The Spring Season will begin in May 2021. The official start date is still to be determined.

Off season/pre-season workouts may not begin before September 21st and will be held at the discretion of the district. A date for the commencement of these workouts at Monroe-Woodbury has not yet been set.

The Athletics Department will be sharing details related specifically to M-W sports soon. Please stay tuned to the district website for more information.

post_text:
On Monday, August 24, Governor Cuomo announced that some lower risk school sports may begin on September 21.

Upon hearing that announcement, NYSPHSAA and sectional executive directors across the state have been working to provide more clarity on this decision. Return to play considerations will be discussed at the county, section and state levels over the next few days.

At all levels, the goal is to provide our student athletes an opportunity to play in a safe environment.

We hope to have more information soon. Thank you for your patience.

post_text: MWFITT Academy was created to help students, parents, guardians and caregivers learn to use the Chromebooks and iPads the district has provided for students. Visit the MWFITT Academy page: https://www.mw.k12.ny.us/academics/instructional-technology/mwfitt-academy/. You will find libraries of step by step videos in English and Spanish to watch on a phone or computer as often as needed. You will also find a Calendar of in person online Question & Answer sessions, also in English and Spanish, with the district's Technology Coaches. Just use a computer to go to the Calendar, click on the Meet link for the session you want and join. You can just listen, or ask a question yourself. It's a great way to learn more! post_text:
On June 16, district residents passed the $183,999,908 proposed budget for the 2020-21 school year by a vote of 3,641 yes votes to 2,296 no votes ‚Äî an approval rating of 61.3 percent. Under the approved budget, the district‚Äôs tax levy is projected to increase by 1.51 percent.

The proposition to purchase 9 school vehicles passed with 3,346 yes votes and 2,592 no votes.

Incumbent Daniel Ezratty was re-elected with 3,653 votes; incumbent Donald Beeler was re-elected with 3,497 votes; and Michael Ciriello was elected with 3,189 votes. Jonathan Huberth had 3,048 votes.

Thank you, M-W voters!

post_text: Welcome to the 2020 Monroe-Woodbury High School Science Research Symposium. This is the 20th annual symposium, presented in virtual format for the first. time. It celebrates the hard work of all the students in the Monroe-Woodbury Science Research Program, and especially of the seniors. The Science Research Program is a three year intensive research study into a topic of the student's choosing. Students apply to the program in their freshman year and then spend 3 years working with a mentor to complete their project. The subjects vary from neural networks to the impacts of cancer and multiple sclerosis treatments. Presentations from sophomores and juniors discuss their initial research. Seniors present their final projects and results. Advisors Mr. Decker and Mrs. Flanagan invite you to enjoy and celebrate these awesome students by visiting their website: https://sites.google.com/mw.k12.ny.us/mw-science-research-symposium/home

Seventh grader Sienna D. has identified a wonderful way to reach out to nursing home residents and staff during the quarantine. While home, Sienna started a care project that she named ‚ÄúJoke Mail.‚Äù Sienna had heard about nursing homes not being allowed to have visitors during this difficult time. To try to lift their spirits, Sienna started sending care packages of postcards with jokes and encouraging messages to be distributed to patients and staff at local nursing homes. Sienna has asked for friends and family to join her in writing some notes. She hopes you will too!

Nice job, Sienna; continue to shine the light of hope! #mwheroes #mwfam #mwhope

Together. We. Are. Stronger.

post_text:
Meals for district students will continue to be provided for pick up on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 11 a.m. ‚Äì 1 p.m. on a weekly basis until further notice. This week's dates are today, Tuesday, March 24 and Thursday, March 26. Pick up locations are Central Valley Elementary School, 45 Route 32, Central Valley and North Main Elementary School, 212 North Main Street, Monroe. Families are asked to bring their own bag to transport food items. If a person requires a special diet, please email foodforthought@mw.k12.n.us and the district will do its best to accommodate the request.

NOTE: Children with a parent or guardian who becomes unemployed or experiences a loss of household income may be eligible for free and reduced price school meals. You may apply at any time during the school year. We urge you to apply as soon as possible so that eligible students can access breakfast and lunch when school resumes. To apply for free or reduced price meals, please apply online on the food services page on the district website.

Pick up locations are Central Valley Elementary School, 45 Route 32, Central Valley and North Main Elementary School, 212 North Main Street, Monroe. Families are asked to bring their own bag to transport food items. If a person requires a special diet, please email foodforthought@mw.k12.n.us and the district will do its best to accommodate the request.

NOTE: Children with a parent or guardian who becomes unemployed or experiences a loss of household income may be eligible for free and reduced price school meals. You may apply at any time during the school year. We urge you to apply as soon as possible so that eligible students can access breakfast and lunch when school resumes. To apply for free or reduced price meals, please apply online on the food services page on the district website.

The Orange County Department of Health (DOH) notified district officials this evening that a M-W student has had direct exposure to a person diagnosed with COVID-19. The student will be quarantined for 14 days. As of today, there are no confirmed cases in Monroe-Woodbury.

The Commissioner of Health indicated that protocols do not call for school closure under these circumstances. However, we believe it is in the best interest of the district to close school for staff and students, including out of district students, tomorrow, Friday, March 13, to allow the custodial team time to thoroughly clean and disinfect our buildings.

We will provide an update on Sunday to all families and staff. Thank you.

Please note: The website is back. Thanks for your patience.

Hundreds of Pine Tree students participated in the Patriot Club‚Äôs annual Valentine‚Äôs Day Card campaign for our troops. The cards were shared with local VA Hospitals and overseas to active military, as far as Japan and Kuwait. What a wonderful outpouring of love for our servicemen and women.

The Pine Tree Patriot Club supports our troops and veterans. The club is made up of students impacted by deployment and students who are committed to supporting our military families. Members meet not only to share experiences with each other, but also to receive support from the school and from other resources.

post_text:
Monroe-Woodbury Middle School students enjoyed applying what they learned in class to a real world project. The Middle School Home and Careers curriculum includes a unit about the elements and principles of design. In collaboration with the M-W community, faculty and an area business, students, along with their teachers Beth Rickli, Stephanie Rizzi, decorated The Tequila Grill in Monroe with a festive holiday theme. M-W families supported their effort by providing many of the decorations included in the display. The project was such a success that the teachers hope to make this an annual part of the curriculum by selecting one area restaurant to decorate every December.

Special thanks to The Tequila Grill for allowing students to participate in hands-on learning.

Come to the Opening Reception for the exhibit of An Artist's Response to Human Rights on Sunday, December 8 between 1:00 and 3:00 p.m. at Orange Hall Gallery on the Middletown Campus of SUNY Orange. Presented by the Orange County Human Rights Commission, the exhibit contains literary and visual artwork inspired by the Universal Declaration of Human Rights adopted by the United Nations on December 10, 1948, created by Orange County high school juniors and seniors.

Congratulations to these 27 M-W Senior Art Majors whose outstanding work will be exhibited. (See a few samples in the Photo Gallery)
Paul Albano, Kayla DeLeon, Danae‚Äô Drews, Evelyn Gonzalez Valle, Michael Paul Hauck, Jake Houle, Cassandra Hughes, Chloe Jean, Alyssa Kamara, Martyna Maczuga, Alexis Matos, Katherine Morgante, Dylan Nytko, Rebecca Pomerantz, Christian Pintos, Rafaella Pipko, Autumn Romano, Eli Ross, Analise Sanchez, Madison Scherne, Brooke Schoen, Juliane Sisto, Maria Spagna, Madison Tamweber, Nicholas Villanueva, Andrew Yi, and Kate Yoon.

post_text: WELCOME BACK! I'm Peggy Hynes Porter from the M-W Class of 1975 wishing you a fabulous first full week and awesome school year. I am currently preparing our home for a hurricane...not a pleasant experience...but I wanted to take a moment to wish you all well. I enjoyed meeting a number of M-W high school students last June at a lunch chat the day prior to our Alumni Mega Reunion. Special thanks to those students who volunteered the day of our reunion. We appreciated how welcoming everyone was as hundreds of us returned home. A few words of wisdom...work hard, continue getting smarter, try to make a positive difference every day, and don't forget to have fun! Create treasured memories like we alums did back in the day when we were M-W students. On Crusaders!

Thanks to generosity of Target, 15 Monroe-Woodbury families recently received gift cards to purchase school supplies at the Back to School Event. This event brought together members of the Woodbury Police Department and the wonderful staff at Target who assisted families with their selections. The children were able to purchase backpacks, school supplies, sneakers and other items to help them get ready for the start of school.

Special thanks to Monroe Target Store Manager Alexis Smyrychynski and her dedicated staff, who work closely with the district to provide these types of events for M-W families. School Social Worker Denise Guerriero coordinates this event and more for M-W families by securing grants, meeting with local vendors and conducting outreach to families.

We're all in this together! #mwfam #mwinspiresuccess

post_text:
The AP Environmental Science class, led by teacher Jill Jeffrey, recently presented their final report of a completed study of water quality in Walton Lake and Earl Reservoir Park to the Moodna Creek Watershed Intermunicipal Council. The Council's small grant program encourages educational experiences and provided this opportunity for M-W students to conduct water analysis of local bodies of water. Students concluded from their results that both locations appear to be healthy bodies of water.

The students presented to representatives of the Council‚Äôs 14 separate municipalities, representatives from the NYS Department of Environmental Conservation, and other interested non-governmental entities with a stake in Moodna.

Pictured, from left: Kelly Morris, Orange County Planning Department; Jay Beaumont, Council Chair; Kayla Komlani, M-W HS Senior; Jill Jeffery, Teacher; Ankur Madaan, M-W HS Senior; Grace Welsh, M-W HS Senior; Brenden Coyne, Mayor, Cornwall-on-Hudson.

post_text: We know it's too soon to think about the end of summer, but the Transportation Department needs information for fall. Bus routes are based on picking up and delivering students to their home address. Families are asked to inform the district BY AUGUST 12 if a child will be picked up and/or dropped off at an alternate location on a daily basis during the coming school year. Even if this information has not changed from last year, families are asked to complete a new form each year. The Babysitter Transportation Request Form is available on the Forms page of the district website and more information is available on the Transportation Department page under District Services. post_text:
Route 32 Traffic Pattern Update from NYS Dept. of Transportation July 31:
The Department of Transportation announced updates to the traffic pattern on Route 32 that will become effective in the next few days. In addition, the Thruway (I-87) Harriman Exit #16 will be closed overnight over the next few weeks, with traffic detoured through Sloatsburg. Please check the district website for details and drive carefully!

ROUTE 32
Motorists on Route 32 will experience a new traffic pattern over the coming days. Northbound traffic will be shifted to the east to create a safe and unobstructed work zone in the median. Both directions of traffic will remain in the current configuration over the Route 17 bridge.

post_text:
Meet Andrew Crespo, member of the Class of 2001, voted Most Likely to Succeed by his classmates...a sign of things to come! Congratulations to Andrew on his appointment as professor of law at Harvard Law School!

Here's what Andrew has to say about M-W:

"I can picture each and every one of my teachers, principals, and coaches back at MW‚Äîfrom Pine Tree through Middle School and High School‚Äîand remember every one of them with such fondness and affection. I‚Äôve been a student and now a teacher at Harvard for over a decade, but the teachers I had at MW are still some of the best educators I‚Äôve met. I think of them, and all my great classmates and friends, each time I pull off at Exit 16 on the Thruway to visit home, and see the trio of schools I attended from 1995 to 2001 (we were the second class to graduate from the ‚Äúnew‚Äù High School). I feel fortunate to have had such a strong foundation for my education, and such a good model for how to educate others."

We're so proud of you, Andrew! #mwinspiresuccess #mwfam #mwalumni
